In 2011, the Village engaged real estate broker U.S. Equities to market the property for redevelopment.
After extensive marketing efforts, three developers were identified and evaluated by the Village Board
over many months: Marquette Investments LLC., Mega Realty, and Streetscape. In February 2014, the
Village Board selected Marquette as the preferred developer and approved Marquette’s Letter of Intent
to develop the property. Since the Letter of Intent was signed, Marquette has been completing due
diligence on the property and working to create development plans for the site. On Monday, September
8, 2014, the Village Board approved a resolution to enter into a purchase/sales agreement that will
permit Marquette Real Estate Investments, LLC to move forward in the process of purchasing and

Retail Core District), located on the north side of

rink, Ale Fest, etc.) and the remaining Village
parking lots and parking for the Lisle Woodridge
Fire Protection District. Figure 2: Site Location
and Zoning Map provides details on the adjacent
designates the subject property’s future land use
as downtown mixed use area with the intent of
the properties being occupied by a variety of complementary and integrated uses, such as, but not
limited to, residential, office, retail, public, entertainment and service commercial uses (Figure 3: Future
Land Use Map). Staff finds that the proposed mixed land use meets the intent of the future land use plan
The petitioner is requesting approval of a mixed-use PUD to be known as
Main Street Village. This PUD proposal consists of two (2), 5-story buildings with 15,000 SF of
commercial space on the ground floor, a second story management and leasing office and 201 apartment
units with indoor parking. The designated commercial spaces will be located on the first floor of
Building 1 along the Main Street frontage and will extend along the Burlington Avenue frontage as well.
There is also a 2,000 SF commercial space identified along the Burlington Avenue frontage in the
southwest corner of Building 2. The buildings being proposed exceed the B-3 District height
requirement of four (4) stories or 50’ in height, whichever is lower. These buildings are five (5) stories
and approximately 65’ in height at the parapet (and 60’ high at the roof line of the flat roof). In
comparison, the mixed-use building located at 1111 Burlington Avenue is four (4) stories (with loft
space above) and 50’ in height as measured from grade to the average distance between the eaves and
This proposed subdivision is intended to consolidate
the existing lots of record and vacate a portion of the Spencer Avenue street right-of-way to create one
development lot as identified on the Main Street Village preliminary plat of subdivision. Once the
consolidation occurs and the Burlington Avenue right-of-way is formally dedicated as street right-of-
way, the total project acreage for this mixed-use PUD will be approximately 2.4 acres. The 20’ strip of
property which contains a dedicated ingress and egress easement for the Lisle Woodridge Fire District
will be maintained to provide access and parking accommodations to the District for fire equipment,
The planned mix-use PUD will consist of 201 apartment units with approximately
15,000 SF of ground floor commercial space. The 201 apartment units will consist of 132 one bedroom
units and 69 two bedroom units. Based upon a review of the Village’s B-3 parking requirements, the
residential component of this project will require 236 parking spaces to accommodate the proposed
apartment unit mix. The private parking garage being proposed will provide 252 parking spaces for
residents. This results in a surplus of 16 parking spaces from a code perspective.
The commercial component of this project has initially been designated as restaurant space and a fitness
center for the purposes of the parking analysis. The restaurant space designation has been utilized as a
placeholder for calculating parking for this project because the requirement of 1 space for every 100 SF
of floor area is more restrictive than the retail and office parking requirements in the B-3 District. In
review of the V3 Parking Assessment dated September 19, 2014; 122 parking spaces are required for the
commercial component of this development. The Village Code does provide a credit of four (4) parking
spaces for commercial uses for each on street parking spaces that is contiguous and lies within the
frontage of the development (in addition to one parking space per two employees). There are 35 on
street parking spaces proposed along Main Street and Burlington Avenue fronting this mixed-use PUD,
resulting in a credit of 140 parking spaces. This results in the on street parking spaces satisfying the B-3
parking requirements for the commercial component of the project.
It should also be noted that there are 199 commuter parking spaces located directly south of this
proposed mixed-use PUD. These commuter parking spaces are available for public parking between
2pm and 2am during the week and all day Saturday and Sunday. These parking spaces are available for
downtown customer and visitor parking and are located across the street from this development and in
close proximity to Main Street. A downtown parking map identifying current on street, metered and
commuter parking spaces has been provided for reference purposes.
A traffic impact study dated September 19, 2014 was prepared by V3 Companies for
the Main Street Village mixed-use PUD. This study was reviewed by the Village’s traffic consultant
and the results of this review have been provided in the memorandum dated October 9, 2014 from James
J. Benes and Associates, Inc. While no significant issues have been initially identified in this review
memorandum, some additional information that has been requested is as follows: 1) traffic generated
for new land uses, 2) Auto Turn analyses for PACE buses utilizing Burlington Avenue via the commuter
lot and 3) potential redesign of the proposed Spencer-Burlington cross walk to avoid pedestrian-vehicle
The landscaping PUD submittal was prepared by Hitchcock Design and the
primary focus of these plans is the streetscape improvements that will be provided (and continued) along
Main Street (including an outdoor dining area), Burlington Avenue, Center Avenue and the vacated
Spencer Avenue pedestrian plaza. All proposed sidewalk pavement, materials, site furnishings and
fencing will match the existing Downtown Main Street streetscape. Other areas of the mixed-use PUD
that will be enhanced with landscaping improvements will be the second floor pool deck in Building 1
and the dog park located in Building 2.
Four (4) sided building elevations have been provided for both Buildings 1 and 2
and these elevations have been revised several times since last fall as the Village Board was evaluating
development proposals from three (3) different companies. This development consists of two (2)
separate buildings which are connected by way of a public outdoor pedestrian plaza where Spencer
Avenue is proposed to be vacated. Each building is also designed with a court yard facing the
Burlington Avenue right-of-way to break up the larger expanses of building façade and add architectural
interest along the Burlington Avenue streetscape.
The petitioner has incorporated staff comments requesting additional brick and stone building materials
and reducing the amount of hardie plank siding on some of the elevations while eliminating stucco from
the project altogether. Metal awning have been provided along the first floor building facades and
metal balconies have been utilized for each residential apartment unit to add visual interest to the
building elevations. Greater variation has been provided in the building cornice line along the Main
Street and Burlington Avenue facades to add architectural interest and to minimize the look of a flat
roofed building. Additional emphasis should also be placed on the north elevations for Buildings 1 and

text.i: 2 in order to vary building materials and reduce the use of the hardie plank product to add some
additional variation and architectural interest to these elevations.

page.text: A variation has been requested for wall signage in accordance with Section 4-4-13(B) of the
Sign Code. This particular section indicates that each building is allowed one wall sign per roadway
frontage. From a practical standpoint, staff has made the determination that each tenant or business in a
multiple tenant building is permitted and allowed one wall sign as long as the surface area of the sign
does not exceed the requirements of the district (or one square foot of signage for every lineal foot of
building frontage). Staff would also recommend that a unified PUD sign plan should be incorporated

text.i: into this project to provide a consistent and unified look between building tenant signage

page.text: This mixed-use PUD is a transit-oriented development (TOD) as identified in the traffic analysis
provided by the petitioner. This type of mixed-use residential and commercial project is designed to
maximize access to public transportation and incorporates features to encourage transit ridership. A
TOD neighborhood typically has a center with a train station or bus stop and is surrounded by mid and
high density residential development with progressively lower-density development spreading outward
The addition of a higher density development in the downtown has the potential of contributing
significantly towards achieving the redevelopment objectives identified in the downtown master plan. A
mixed-use PUD does add a critical element of new residents, businesses and customers to support local
businesses in the downtown. The design of a mixed-use project offers the ability for residents to live,
work and play all within walking distance of each other, contributing to the sustainable development of
the Village, while at the same time curbing urban sprawl.

As requested, we have reviewed the traffic impact study for two proposed multi-use structures at
the subject site. We have been provided with the following items for review:
1. Traffic Impact Study prepared by V3 Companies of Woodridge, IL (V3) and dated
2. Parking Assessment prepared by V3 dated September 19, 2014
3. Preliminary Engineering Plans for Main Street Village prepared by V3 and dated 8/8/14
4. Main Street Village – Marquette Companies plan sheets A 401 through A 405, A 410 and
A 801 prepared by Humphreys & Partners Architects L.P. and dated 9/11/14.
The proposed development consists of two structures. Each structure will have first floor
commercial land use. Projected first floor land uses include a health/fitness club and
different types of eateries. Upper stories will contain 201 residential apartment dwelling
units. There will be on-site parking for the residences. Commercial parking will use off-site,
on-street parking. Off-site parking will be changed. Specifically, angle parking will be
installed on the north side of Burlington Avenue east of Spencer Avenue. Parallel spaces
will be added to the north side of Burlington Avenue west of Spencer Avenue. One row of
parking northeast of the site will be reconfigured.
Spencer Avenue north of Burlington Avenue will no longer intersect with Burlington.
We find the proposed vehicular trip generation in Table 1 of the Traffic Impact Study for the
listed land uses to be reasonable. We agree with the reduction based upon census tract
data for non-vehicular trips. The reduction for external trips complies with ITE guidelines.
We feel that the assumption that 25% of restaurant trips will be walk-in from either existing
nearby land uses or from transit is not conservative. However, when evaluating the
individual intersections, the impact on projected traffic operations between the approach
used by V3 and a more conservative walk-in assumption is minimal.
We are comfortable with the projected existing traffic redistribution due to closure of
Spencer Avenue at Burlington Avenue, and the projected site traffic distribution used in
Figures 8 through 10. However, a description and exhibit of the estimated directional
distribution percentages for traffic generated by the new land uses should be included in the
The conclusion that intersections around the development will operate at acceptable levels
The addition of angle parking on Burlington east of Spencer eliminates the merging area
now used by northbound traffic exiting the commuter parking lot wishing to turn left onto
Burlington. The development correctly proposes to change the northbound approach of
Center-Burlington to a separate left turn and a through-right turn lane. The closing of
Spencer north of Burlington offers an opportunity to revise the operation of the commuter
parking lot entrance south of Burlington and opposite existing Spencer Avenue. The south
leg could be converted to a full access where motorists leaving the parking areas could turn
left onto Burlington Avenue. This could reduce the existing congestion at Center-Burlington.
Should the commuter lot entrance be converted to two-way traffic, we would recommend
that the current PACE bus circulation be maintained, requiring the buses to continue to exit
only at Center Avenue, and that the Center Avenue exit remain one-way outbound.
The narrowed Burlington Avenue cross-section requires confirmation that PACE buses can
negotiate the new curb returns; specifically left turn exits from the commuter lot to
westbound Burlington. The applicant should provide AutoTurn analyses to demonstrate
that buses can navigate the turn satisfactorily.
Additionally, an AutoTurn analysis is required for the westbound Burlington to northbound
Main Street right turn movement for buses due to the proposed reduction in corner radius.
The existing parking lot entrance opposite Spencer should also be analyzed using AutoTurn
to verify that if converted to two-way automobile operation, a PACE bus can enter the lot
from Burlington while automobile is waiting to exit the commuter parking lot.
Due to the closure of Spencer Avenue at Burlington Avenue, we recommend that a No
Outlet sign be posted for southbound traffic on Spencer just south of School Street.
The pedestrian counts in Figure 6 suggest in the morning pedestrians access the inbound
train station from Main Street and Center Avenue. This is not a surprise given the location
of the grade-separated track crossings. We expect this morning walking pattern to continue.
The building layouts should be sensitive to this predominant pedestrian movement. In the
evening, the pedestrian traffic from the outbound train platform is more diffuse as no track
crossing is required. This evening walking pattern is expected to continue.
Today there is public sidewalk on the west side of Spencer south of Burlington. A
preponderance of pedestrian traffic today crosses Spencer-Burlington on the west side.
However, the proposal shows a pedestrian crossing on the east side of Spencer-Burlington.
We suggest the west side be considered as the more direct walking path. Although it is
longer across Burlington on the west side, the proposed decorative island on the north side
of Burlington could be moved west to reduce the crossing length. If all-way stop control
remains at Spencer-Burlington, possible conflicts with pedestrian and possible northbound
left turning vehicles would be resolved.
There are potential pedestrian-vehicle conflicts where the proposed garage access
driveways for both buildings cross the public sidewalk. We recommend stop control for
vehicular traffic exiting the garages and further investigation of other measures to increase
visibility of pedestrians passing the garage doors.
The calculated required number of parking spaces contained in Table 2 of the Parking
Assessment complies with Village code for its distribution of dwelling units for residential
uses and based on square footage for commercial uses. The number of parking spaces
provided on-site and on-street exceed the minimum required spaces as computed in Table
2 with the application of the on-street parking credit. The parking garages provide all
required spaces for residential land use plus small unassigned surplus. The assignment of
surplus internal spaces should be discussed.
In order to meet ADA requirements for number of handicap accessible parking spaces in
the garages, the surplus must be reduced by four spaces, two in each building, in order to
create the minimum number of ADA parking spaces in each building. There are an
adequate number of handicap accessible parking spaces provided on-street in accordance
with the Provisional Right-of-Way Accessible Guidelines.
The regulation of on-street parking should be discussed to address discouraging long-term
employee or commuter use. Provisions for overnight residential visitor parking are not
The parking spaces meet the size requirements of Section 5-13-1-5 of the Village Code
except for the stall length and bay width in spaces without overhang (subsections H2 and
H4). We understand the applicant will ask for a variation. The spaces shown should
Ramp slopes of 9.5% and 10% are shown in the west building garage. These slopes are
acceptable provided grade transitions are constructed to prevent vehicles bottoming out.
No transitions are currently shown on the plans.
We understand the internal parking spaces will be assigned. The proposed dead end
parking aisles without turnarounds in the garages are not a problem if all spaces are
Our interpretation of Section 5-13-2-6 of the Village code is that one loading space is
required per building. One 12’ wide by 65’ long space is proposed for the development. It
appears that an exception may be necessary to allow one loading space for the
development. The applicant should provide an AutoTurn analysis demonstrating that a
tractor-trailer moving van or delivery truck can enter and exit the loading space.
